# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__ across all 8 mp subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __invert__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __floor__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __ceil__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# The proxy types (_BaseSetProxy, _BaseDictProxy, BaseListProxy) are the most
#   analytically interesting subjects here. _BaseSetProxy proxies set, which
#   has no __invert__, __floor__, or __ceil__ — set is a collection, not a
#   number, and its algebra uses binary operators only. _BaseDictProxy proxies
#   dict — dict has no integer inversion or rounding operators. BaseListProxy
#   proxies list — list has no integer inversion or rounding operators.
#   Even BaseListProxy, which in wave 658 exposed __add__ and __mul__ (the only
#   true results across all mp waves 658–670), defines neither __invert__ nor
#   __floor__ nor __ceil__, because list items may have magnitude but the list
#   container itself has no numeric rounding semantics.
# multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its types interact
#   exclusively through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management,
#   and IPC — never through Python's integer inversion or numeric rounding
#   data model operators.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

